\v 18 All the builders carried \w a|strong="H3068"\w* sword strapped to their side, and the trumpeter stood beside me.\f + \fr 4:18 \ft To provide warning on an attack.\f*
\p 
\v 19 Then I told the nobles, the officials, and the rest of the people: “We have \w a|strong="H3068"\w* lot to do everywhere, so \w we|strong="H3068"\w*'re very spread out along the wall.
\v 20 Wherever you are and you hear the sound of the trumpet, run to join us there. Our God will fight for us!”
\p 
\v 21 We went on working, with half of the men holding spears from dawn until the stars came out.
\v 22 I also told the people, “Everyone including servants must spend the night inside Jerusalem, so they can be on guard duty at night and work during the day.”
\v 23 During that time none of us changed our clothes—not me or my brothers or my men or the guards with me. Everyone carried their weapons at all times, even to go for water.\f + \fr 4:23 \ft “Everyone carried their weapons at all times, even to go for water.” The Hebrew is unclear. Literally it reads “each his weapon the water.”\f*
\b
\c 5
\p 
\v 1 Around \w this|strong="H1961"\w* \w time|strong="H1961"\w* \w some|strong="H5971"\w* \w people|strong="H5971"\w* \w and|strong="H1419"\w* \w their|strong="H1961"\w* wives \w started|strong="H1961"\w* \w a|strong="H3068"\w* tremendous argument \w with|strong="H5971"\w* \w the|strong="H1961"\w* other \w Jews|strong="H3064"\w*.
